@node WHATDLOCK "Drive Lock v1.00 - What is Drive Lock?"
@toc CONTENTS
                            What is Drive Lock?

 Drive Lock, now referred to as DLock, provides a quick, GUI way of write-
 protecting drives and partitions from the Workbench.  It is possible to
 configure DLock to write-protect multiple drives or partitions immediately
 from one command or double-click.


              @{"     Disclaimer      " link DISCLAIMER} @{"     Using DLock     " link USING}
              @{" What is Drive Lock? " link WHATDLOCK} @{"  Acknowledgements   " link ACK}
              @{"    Requirements     " link REQUIREMENTS} @{"     Contacting      " link CONTACT}
              @{"    Installation     " link INSTALL} @{"       History       " link HISTORY}
@endnode

@node REQUIREMENTS "Drive Lock v1.00 - Requirements"
@toc CONTENTS
                               Requirements

         DLock can only be used on systems running OS2 or greater.
         ReqTools.library must be in the libs: directory.
         The Lock command must also be in the c: directory.


              @{"     Disclaimer      " link DISCLAIMER} @{"     Using DLock     " link USING}
              @{" What is Drive Lock? " link WHATDLOCK} @{"  Acknowledgements   " link ACK}
              @{"    Requirements     " link REQUIREMENTS} @{"     Contacting      " link CONTACT}
              @{"    Installation     " link INSTALL} @{"       History       " link HISTORY}
@endnode

@node INSTALL "Drive Lock v1.00 - Installation"
@toc CONTENTS
                               Installation

The easiest way of installing DLock is by dragging the DLock icon into the
WBStartup drawer on your boot partition.

DLock can also be installed in the User-Startup.  Just insert the following
to your s:User-Startup :-
                           Run >nil: <nil: DLock


              @{"     Disclaimer      " link DISCLAIMER} @{"     Using DLock     " link USING}
              @{" What is Drive Lock? " link WHATDLOCK} @{"  Acknowledgements   " link ACK}
              @{"    Requirements     " link REQUIREMENTS} @{"     Contacting      " link CONTACT}
              @{"    Installation     " link INSTALL} @{"       History       " link HISTORY}
@endnode
@node USING "Drive Lock v1.00 - Using DLock"
@toc CONTENTS
                                Using DLock

DLock can be started by double-clicking on the icon from Workbench, running
it from CLI/Shell, from Nico François' ToolDaemon, or Stefan Becker's
Toolmanager, etc.

When DLock is executed for the first time, you will be presented with a window
which has two distinct areas :-

              @{"  Run Preferences   " link RUNPREFS} First third on the left
              @{" Main Volume Window " link MAINVOLWIN} The remaining part of the window

         There is also a small section for locking @{" Floppy Drives " link FLOPPY}.


              @{"     Disclaimer      " link DISCLAIMER} @{"     Using DLock     " link USING}
              @{" What is Drive Lock? " link WHATDLOCK} @{"  Acknowledgements   " link ACK}
              @{"    Requirements     " link REQUIREMENTS} @{"     Contacting      " link CONTACT}
              @{"    Installation     " link INSTALL} @{"       History       " link HISTORY}
@endnode

@node RUNPREFS "Drive Lock v1.00 - Using DLock - Run Preferences"
@toc CONTENTS
                             Run Preferences

  This box lets you configure the way DLock will act when run.  There are
  four preference settings :-

                           @{" Run With Window  " link RUNWIN}
                           @{"  Drives Tagged   " link DRIVESTAGGED}
                           @{" After Doing Tags " link AFTERTAGS}
                           @{"     Password     " link PASSWORD}

  These preference settings are saved in the @{" preference file " link SAVEPREFS}.


               @{"     Using DLock    " link USING} @{ " Main Volume Window " link MAINVOLWIN}
               @{"   Run Preferences  " link RUNPREFS} @{ "    Floppy Drives   " link FLOPPY}
@endnode

@node RUNWIN "Drive Lock v1.00 - Using DLock - Run Preferences - Run With Window"
@toc CONTENTS
                              Run With Window

               This governs the state DLock will open on :-

     O Full Size -> DLock runs with its window fully open.

     O Zoomed    -> DLock runs with its window Zipped, ie. iconified.

     O Closed    -> DLock runs, but doesn't open its window.
                    NOTE: When this option is selected, DLock will
                    automatically exit after locking drives.  You can
                    over-ride this option by running DLock with the
                    following options :-

                    From Shell, type : "Run DLock Open"
                    Set WB ToolType  : "FORCE_OPEN=YES"


                 @{"   Run Preferences  " link RUNPREFS} @{"  After Doing Tags  " link AFTERTAGS}
                 @{"  Run With Window   " link RUNWIN} @{"      Password      " link PASSWORD}
                 @{"   Drives Tagged    " link DRIVESTAGGED} @{"  Preference file   " link SAVEPREFS}
@endnode

@node DRIVESTAGGED "Drive Lock v1.00 - Using DLock - Run Preferences - Drives Tagged"
@toc CONTENTS
                               Drives Tagged

              This tells DLock how to handle Tagged Volumes.

   O Shown Only  -> When DLock runs, any "Volumes" that are Tagged
                    will not be Locked.

   O Lock Drives -> All "Volumes" that have been Tagged Will be Locked.


               @{"   Run Preferences  " link RUNPREFS} @{"  After Doing Tags  " link AFTERTAGS}
               @{"  Run With Window   " link RUNWIN} @{"      Password      " link PASSWORD}
               @{"   Drives Tagged    " link DRIVESTAGGED} @{"  Preference file   " link SAVEPREFS}
@endnode

@node AFTERTAGS "Drive Lock v1.00 - Using DLock - Run Preferences - After Doing Tags"
@toc CONTENTS
                             After Doing Tags

       This tells DLock what to do after it acts on Tagged Volumes.

   O Stay Active  -> Open DLock window as defined in "Run With Window".

   O Exit Program -> Exit DLock after acting on Tagged Volumes.


               @{"   Run Preferences  " link RUNPREFS} @{"  After Doing Tags  " link AFTERTAGS}
               @{"  Run With Window   " link RUNWIN} @{"      Password      " link PASSWORD}
               @{"   Drives Tagged    " link DRIVESTAGGED} @{"  Preference file   " link SAVEPREFS}
@endnode

@node PASSWORD "Drive Lock v1.00 - Using DLock - Run Preferences - Password"
@toc CONTENTS
                                 Password

You can enter a four digit password in this box.  The password can consist
of any four characters in the ASCII character set. eg.

                                   2344
                                   qwer
                                   @1z©
                                   A0c-


                @{"   Run Preferences  " link RUNPREFS} @{"  After Doing Tags  " link AFTERTAGS}
                @{"  Run With Window   " link RUNWIN} @{"      Password      " link PASSWORD}
                @{"   Drives Tagged    " link DRIVESTAGGED} @{"  Preference file   " link SAVEPREFS}
@endnode

@node SAVEPREFS "Drive Lock v1.00 - Using DLock - Run Preferences - Preference File"
@toc CONTENTS
  The preferences can be save using the Save Prefs gadget.  The following
  information will be saved to the preference file :-

  a)  The @{" Run Preferences " link RUNPREFS} window.
  b)  The @{" Main Volume " link MAINVOLWIN} window.
  c)  The x and y position of the DLock window when fully open and also
      when zipped.

  The filename of the preference file can be anything, but the default is
  "DLock.prefs".  It is saved in both env: and envarc:.

  The Load Prefs gadget will load a new preference file.


               @{"   Run Preferences  " link RUNPREFS} @{"  After Doing Tags  " link AFTERTAGS}
               @{"  Run With Window   " link RUNWIN} @{"      Password      " link PASSWORD}
               @{"   Drives Tagged    " link DRIVESTAGGED} @{"  Preference file   " link SAVEPREFS}
@endnode

@node MAINVOLWIN "Drive Lock v1.00 - Using DLock - Main Volume Window"
@toc CONTENTS
                            Main Volume Window

  This is where all the drives/partitions to be locked can be selected.

  The hard-drive/partition can be configured in the collection of gadgets
  shown below :-

        Lock ON/OFF          Volume Names                    Tags
          ________________________________________________
         |  __     |                                | ==\ |  ____
       1 | |_  R/W |                                ||__| | |    |
         |_________|________________________________|_____| |____|

             (a)                 (b)                  (c)     (d)

This cycle gadget toggles between R/W and Lock.  It immediately
write-enables and write-protects the drive/partition specified in Volume
Names (b).  The Volume Name can be specified by simply typing the device
name into the string gadget.  The device name can also be selected from a
volume requester by clicking on gadget (c).  When the check-box gadget (d)
is checked, that device will be locked when DLock is next executed.  If
left blank, then that device will be made write-enabled.  Also see the
@{" Drives Tagged " link DRIVESTAGGED} section.

Currently, only three banks of eight devices can be setup.  If you have
more than twenty-four devices, you have too many and can donate one to
me 8-).

The device names and the states of the tags of all three banks are
saved in the @{" preference file " link SAVEPREFS}.

The gadgets at the bottom right of the DLock window effect the whole
drive/partition bank.  Display Bank selects which bank of devices to edit.
There are three banks of eight to choose from.  Lock and Unlock Bank
simply locks or unlocks all displayed devices.  Tag and UnTag Bank tags
or untags the displayed devices.

               @{"     Using DLock    " link USING} @{ " Main Volume Window " link MAINVOLWIN}
               @{"   Run Preferences  " link RUNPREFS} @{ "    Floppy Drives   " link FLOPPY}
@endnode

@node FLOPPY "Drive Lock v1.00 - Using DLock - Floppy Drive Window"
@toc CONTENTS
                            Floppy Drive Window

 Under the bank of eight @{" drive/partition " link MAINVOLWIN} gadgets, there are four floppy
 drive check-box gadgets.  These write-protect and write-enable the disk
 in the respective drive.  Of course, if the floppy is physically
 write-protected, ie. the tab is open, then there is no way of
 write-enabling it.  Note:  The lock state of floppy drives are not saved
 in the @{" preferences " link SAVEPREFS}.


               @{"     Using DLock    " link USING} @{ " Main Volume Window " link MAINVOLWIN}
               @{"   Run Preferences  " link RUNPREFS} @{ "    Floppy Drives   " link FLOPPY}
@endnode

